Poll: Americans split on Gonzales' future

WASHINGTON (CNN) -- As Attorney General Alberto Gonzales prepares to testify before Congress Thursday about the firings
of several U.S. attorneys, a new CNN/Opinion Research Corporation Poll shows Americans are split over whether he should
leave office.

Thirty eight percent of Americans think the attorney general should resign, while 37 percent think he should remain in
his post. Another 24 percent were unsure what Gonzales should do. When asked if Bush should fire Gonzales, 31 percent
said yes, 36 percent answered no and 33 percent responded that they were unsure.

Gonzales' favorable rating was 28 percent, while 33 percent of Americans had an unfavorable impression and 39 percent
had neither a positive or negative view of him.

Gonzales has been criticized for the firing of eight U.S. attorneys allegedly for political reasons. The Senate
Judiciary Committee today is expected to question him extensively about his involvement as well as what role the White
House might have played in the dismissals.

"Most people aren't paying attention to this news story because it doesn't touch on any issue that affects them
directly," CNN's Senior Political Analyst Bill Schneider said. "Most people haven't formed a firm opinion."

-- CNN's Lauren Kornreich

